  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Developing a sustainable and resilient cold chain to facilitate access to COVID-19 tools</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">UNIDO as a specialized agency in cooperation with WHO that is the leading authority on scientific and public health information, are going to implement a joint program in Iran to develop sustainable cooling in health care system to support resilient recovery in the country . Responding to COVID-19 pandemic has highlighted the necessity of access to reliable space cooling and refrigeration services to people#s well-being and facilitating the delivery of vaccines, medical products, and food in an uninterrupted temperature-controlled chain. This program aims to demonstrate the efficient and climate-friendly medical and commercial cooling to be sustained by circular business models in the health sector. It will address the space cooling and refrigeration provision challenges across the health care system in terms of equipment, buildings, cold chains, rules and regulations and the professionals who run the infrastructure and work in this system. This would support government plans to strengthen the country&apos;s healthcare system to combat the pandemic. It also facilitates smooth economic recovery by strengthening resilient economic structures, creates new jobs and protects vulnerable populations and accelerate the transition to efficient climate friendly cooling technologies in different sectors (e.g., agri-food). In s</narrative>
  </description>
